
[1]catarrh

   CATARRH, n. catar. A defluxion, or increased secretion of mucus from
   the membranes of the nose, fauces and bronchiae, with fever, sneezing
   cough, thirst, lassitude and loss of appetite, and sometimes an entire
   loss of taste; called also a cold, coryza. An epidemic catarrh is
   called Influenza.
